pe that he might buy it\nlater for twenty cents. There is\na bottom even to prices. By and\nby you will be asking yourself,\n\"why didn't I buy when I had the\nchance?\"\nWhiskey is a tricky friend, a\nlying medicine, a deadly master.\nonk Eastman, greatest of all\ngunmen and gangsters, is found\nmurdered. The pce were puz\ngild that the h 'ad'tiller should\nbe so easily killed. But Eastman\nhad been deali in bootleg whis\nkey, and DRIKING it as well\nas selling it. The doctor after the\nautopsy said, \"Monk Eastman was\nvery drunk.\" That explains it all.\nWhiskey is the greatest gunman,\nespecially bootleg whiskey.\nNearly a thousand dined with\nHoover on Wednesday. Each paid\na thousand dollars for the dinner.\nEach ate a plate of rice, cup of\ncocoa, a small piece of bread\nnothing else. Profit on the dinner\nwent to poor children in Europe.\nThat dinner would be profitable\nalso to the nine hundred that ate\nit if they could learn from it that\nsuch a meal, eaten every day, at\nnoon, or in the evening, would\nlengthen life by twenty years on\nthe average.\nMarshall Field, 3d, grandson of\nthe great Chicago merchant, is go\ning into business IN CHICAGO, in\nspite of the fact that he has more\nmoney than he needs now and will\nhave scores of millions more later.\nHe isn't marrying any Greek\nKing's niece, or settling in Eng\nland, or even at Newport. He has\nstarted in to work as his grand\nfather worked, and will spend the\nField money where his grandfather\nmade it-a pleasant change from\nthe average. It is to be hoped\nMarshall Field can see that grand\nson. IN CHICAGO. which to Mar\nshall Field was the central flower\nbed in the garden of Eden.\nIt looked as though d'Annunzio\nwould have to die fighting. But\niuckily a poet has many ideas, and\nd'Annunzio has flown away in a\nflying machine, leaving word that\nhis countrymen, who concentrated\non \"their Christmas greediness\nwhile we were assassinated by\ntheir government,\" were not worth\ndying for.\nD'Annunzio is conquered, but\nhis nation owes him a great deal.\nHe held in check the greed or in.\ndifference of Italy's allies, that\nwould have deprived Italy of even\na pretense of justice. To the cour\nage and genius of d'Annunzio\nItaly owes the influence that she\nretains in the Adriatic.\nIt is said that d'Annunzio will\nnow go to South America, which\nwould be a mistake. Europe is\nthe place for him. lie will p rob\nably turn up In Paris or Monte\nCarlo, and think uip a new idea.\nwhile talking to beautiful ladies\nas wild as himself. Ihis life has\nnot been dull.\nBad news of another great\nItalian, Caruqo. His illness takes a\nserious turn. Such a genius is\nto music what eyesight Is to a pic\nture or a sunset. Without the\neye the picture does not exist.\nWithout the voice of Caruso the\nreal beauty of the music does not\nF exist. When his day comes--mny\nit be many years hence--the world\nshould build a fine monument to\nCaruso. The world will delight in\nhis voce preserved by 'cience,\nlong after it ceases to talk of the\nHUGE I\nYET INSURANCE\nHEAD AROUSED\nCol. Cholmely-Jones Arraigns\nSenators Who Would Merge\nWork With Pensions.\nA \"raw deal\" would be inflicted\nupon every ex-service man gmnong\nthe 4,500,000 who joined the colors,\nincluding both those insured and\nthose eligible to the law's benefits,\nif Congress heeds suggestions nade\nin some quarters that the War Risk\nBureau has been a \"failure\" and al\nlows it to disintegrate or he absorbed\nby other departmenti.\nASSAILS PL.I IGNORAN'E.\nCol. R. 0. Cholmeley .lones. Dirie\ntor of the Bureau today'thus answered\nthe attacks upon the llur.au and its\nfuture usefulness. \"'Vure igioranw,--\"\nof the Ilureau's 11unctions undier the\nlaw and its accomplishments to be\nAtow upon disabled ser%ic men the I\nhenefits Congress intended is at th'\nroot of most of the \"wild statements\"\nnow heard, ('o. Ciolmeley .Jonesco as\nsurted.\n\"Various units of the War Risk nre\nnow being consolidattd andl to